  "prompt": "what are the ethical principles and core values that govern the social work profession in America?",
  "response": "The National Association of Social Workers (NASW) has established a Code of Ethics that outlines the core values and ethical principles that guide social work practice in the United States. These include:\n\nCore Values:\n1. Service\n- Commitment to helping people in need\n- Addressing social problems and challenges\n- Promoting social justice and social change\n\n2. Social Justice\n- Challenging social inequities\n- Promoting equal access to resources\n- Respecting diversity and individual differences\n- Confronting discrimination and oppression\n\n3. Dignity and Worth of the Person\n- Treating each individual with respect\n- Recognizing the inherent value of all people\n- Promoting client self-determination\n- Respecting individual rights and potential\n\n4. Importance of Human Relationships\n- Recognizing relationships as fundamental to social work practice\n- Promoting cooperation and collaboration\n- Supporting healthy interpersonal connections\n\n5. Integrity\n- Behaving in a trustworthy manner\n- Maintaining professional boundaries\n- Being honest and responsible\n\nEthical Principles:\n1. Respect for client self-determination\n2. Promoting client welfare\n3. Avoiding conflicts of interest\n4. Maintaining professional competence\n5. Protecting client confidentiality\n6. Practicing within professional boundaries\n7. Maintaining professional integrity\n\nThese values and principles guide social workers in providing ethical, compassionate, and effective services to individuals, families, groups, and communities.",
